               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-229-person1974">
                  JAMES 
                  WRIGGLESWORTH
               <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1974" type="surname" value="WRIGGLESWORTH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1974" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1974" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I lost a wheelbarrow some time before the 4th of November; one of my men found it that day in posssesion of the officer.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-229-person1975">
                  JOHN 
                  BARNES
               <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1975" type="surname" value="BARNES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1975" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1975" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I bought the barrow of the prisoner about nine weeks ago.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CHURCHILL. Q. Did not he bring another man with him? A. Yes - but the other man did not say it was his; the prisoner told me he had an old barrow to sell - he did not say for another man; I paid 4s. and a pot of beer for it, at the Dublin Castle public-house, Park-street - I laid the money on the table; I do not know which took it up: the prisoner bargained to sell it to me.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-229-person1976">
                  WILLIAM 
                  COLTON
               <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1976" type="surname" value="COLTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1976" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1976" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , I found the barrow in possession of Barnes, at the Scotch school, in the New North-road- he said he got it from Richardson, and I took him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-229-person1977">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BARTLETT
               <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1977" type="surname" value="BARTLETT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1977" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1977" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I understood that the prisoner was wanted - he was taken, and asked what I wanted with him; I said on suspicion of stealing a barrow - he said,"That barrow which Barnes the gardener had of me?" I said, Yes - he said, "I found that in one of the shrubberies in the Regent's-park - I sold it to Barnes for 4s. and a pot of beer.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-229-person1978">
                  JOHN 
                  WRIGGLESWORTH
               <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1978" type="surname" value="WRIGGLESWORTH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1978" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-229-person1978" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. My barrow was lost from the brick-field, in the road near Holloway - it is worth 10s. or 12s.; the place was trenched round to keep strangers out - he must have got it at night.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18281204-229-verdict1208" type="verdictDescription">
